1. Here we are setting a default value, below is a example: 

#           assigning a default value
def greeting(name = "Ruby programmer")
  puts "Hello, #{name}"
end

if run, it will give me:
  "Hello, Ruby programmer"

# by adding a [=] within the argument, it makes it a default value. if i don't write a name in the argument, it will use the default value.

2. If i have a default value, but I still do set a name to the argument, it will use the set name and not the argument. For exmaple:

def greeting(name = "Ruby programmer")
  puts "Hello, #{name}"
end

greeting("Spohie")

if run, it will give me:
  "Hello, Sophie"

3. I can also do a 2 argument method with 1 of the 2 arguments being a default value. 
def greeting(name, language="Ruby")
  puts "Hello, #{name}. We heard you are a great #{language} programmer."
end

# the default arguments/value most always be at the end. if its in the front, it wouldn't read the argument.